Strictly speaking this particular case never happens, right?  Once .panning is added, that means you've actually started the pan and .mousedown also applies so the rule below takes precedence.  And when .mousedown ends, panning also ends, so this rule won't take effect then either.

I think this rule only needs to cover the case when alt is pressed and there's no drag-zooming happening.

At this point, it seems perhaps easier to to move the key/mouse event handling logic entirely into the PanZoomDragLayer (it's already partially in there due to the mouse filters).  Then it would be easier to express these rules very directly as just:

```
if panning:
  cursor = grabbing
else if drag-zooming:
  cursor = crosshair
else if altdown:
  cursor = grab
else:
  cursor = crosshair
```

I agree. The problem is there are two parts - request and response headers. We want to display request headers before sending the request, so they have to be torn apart. 

Also, `stderr` may contain other trash like `command ran in 4.608 seconds.`, so it is not a good practice to extract info from `stderr`. 

For the `Authorization` header, the current behavior of msrest with `--debug` is to totally remove it. We previously also removed similar information with https://github.com/Azure/azure-cli/pull/10473 due to security concerns. So currently let's just hide it until we get approval from PM @achandmsft .

What I am thinking is to add a param `--include-headers`, so that result in `stdout` will become something like:

```jsonc
{
    "request": {
        "headers": {
            "User-Agent": "AZURECLI/2.0.81",
            "x-ms-client-request-id": "b43346df-c51f-475a-bf7d-eec64d394f15",
            "CommandName": "rest",
            "ParameterSetName": "-u --verbose"
        }
    },
    "response": {
        "headers": {
            "Cache-Control": "no-cache",
            "Pragma": "no-cache",
            "Content-Type": "application/json; charset=utf-8",
            "Content-Encoding": "gzip",
            "Expires": "-1",
            "Vary": "Accept-Encoding",
            "x-ms-ratelimit-remaining-subscription-reads": "11999",
            "x-ms-request-id": "05761bc6-1b26-44be-a676-a6999e950a8a",
            "x-ms-correlation-request-id": "05761bc6-1b26-44be-a676-a6999e950a8a",
            "x-ms-routing-request-id": "EASTASIA:20200210T113239Z:05761bc6-1b26-44be-a676-a6999e950a8a",
            "Strict-Transport-Security": "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains",
            "X-Content-Type-Options": "nosniff",
            "Date": "Mon, 10 Feb 2020 11:32:38 GMT",
            "Content-Length": "279"
        },
        "status": 200,
        "body": {
            "id": "/subscriptions/0b1f6471-1bf0-4dda-aec3-cb9272f09590/resourceGroups/xxx",
            "location": "southeastasia",
            "name": "xxx",
            "properties": {
                "provisioningState": "Succeeded"
            },
            "type": "Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups"
        }
    }
}
```

In thus case, the output can be easily scripted from `stdout` instead of `stderr`. Any suggestion is welcome.

